    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2080846798" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2080846798" />
    <a title="Robin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/40519180-robin"><img alt="Robin" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2080846798?book_show_action=true">Aug 05, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Robin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Robin" href="/user/show/40519180-robin">Robin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/11490086-firefly-summer">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2080846798" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13885176431728734708">I usually choose to read Maeve Binchy&apos;s novels as comfort reads. However, I am also well aware there is more to her work than comfort. She has a gentle, but nevertheless, intrinsic feminist streak in all her works which enhances them without detracting from their merit for non-feminist readers. In Firefly Summer, one of the American protagonists states that she has tried to help the women in the small Irish village in which she lives for a short time, combining her profession and romantic intere</span>
  <span id="freeText13885176431728734708" style="display:none">I usually choose to read Maeve Binchy's novels as comfort reads. However, I am also well aware there is more to her work than comfort. She has a gentle, but nevertheless, intrinsic feminist streak in all her works which enhances them without detracting from their merit for non-feminist readers. In Firefly Summer, one of the American protagonists states that she has tried to help the women in the small Irish village in which she lives for a short time, combining her profession and romantic interests. Rachel recognises the limits placed on the women by their environment as well as the men around them. In many ways this is ironic as her acceptance of her secondary role in her lover's life is as imprisoning as the constrains affecting the other women in the novel. By the end of the novel , the most physically constrained is Kate Ryan, initially the most active in mind and body. <br /><br />The conflict, friendship between an American, returning to his Irish roots, and the Irish villagers is the main storyline. Together with his children and Rachel they bring into the village a need to find a way between change and custom; money making and maintaining traditional businesses and practices; and cultural differences. Friendships blossom and wane; a court case demonstrates the impact of village sentiment on the victim and its capacity to allow unhealthy business practice to triumph (unknown to the village and victim); a death provides some soul searching amongst the teenagers.<br /><br />Binchy is a consummate story teller and her characterisation, particularly of young people, is skilful. However, I was found this novel less appealing than her others. To me, some aspects of the storyline did not fit together smoothly, and it seemed as though Binchy was less at home with depicting the conflicts between an American dream than the Irish aspirations that furnish much of the material in her other novels. To be fair, Binchy portrays the American woman who comes to Dublin in Tara Road as a sympathetic character, although quite different from her Irish hosts. But in some ways this makes the difficulties I see in story of Patrick O'Neill's sojourn in Mountfern less easy to understand. The irony of the result of his aspirations and those of the original landowners he is seeking to emulate with his rebuilding of Fernscourt is quite compelling, but also jarring. He is a self-made business man whose aspirations are tempered in some ways by his desire to be part of the community; the original English owners whose forbears forced the O'Neills to leave Ireland had no such interest. The link between them is tenuous, undermining that part of the story line. <br /><br />It is possible that this novel aspired to be a broader look at American/Irish relations when those forced to move to America (or Australia) return. However, it did not lend itself to Binchy's usual deft treatment. So, on re-reading years after my initial read, I am slightly disappointed. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13885176431728734708" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

